EQ + Tech =3D Employee Happiness? Companies Want to Find Out


By Amanda Gerut =
<https://www.agendaweek.com/email-contributor/100834/3343244/424884>   =
October 1, 2021

A new executive role appointed at several companies in the past year =
ties together technology, employee experience, engagement, well-being =
and data into a modern, tech-steeped head of employee experience.=20

JPMorgan Chase & Co. in May appointed chief information officer James =
Reid to an employee experience role focused on updating the =
company=E2=80=99s internal technology to improve the way employees work. =
Similarly, Raytheon in 2020 appointed Kelly Candler to vice president of =
digital workplace and employee experience, while Salesforce appointed =
former chief technology officer Jill Tucker as vice president of =
enterprise IT and employee experience.=20

Josh King, search firm Ridgeway Partners=E2=80=99 technology practice =
lead, noted the trend in his recent third-quarter newsletter =
<https://ridgewaypartners.com/ridgeway-partners-tech-leaders-on-the-move-=
q3-2021/>  and pointed to its potential impact on employee happiness and =
retention. He wrote that average employee tenure is only 1.1 years at =
Google, 1.8 years at Uber Technologies and 2.1 years at Dropbox, =
indicating room for improvement.=20

According to King, the newly appointed employee experience executives =
are typically former in-house tech leaders who are skilled at vendor =
management and have a good sense of the various types of software =
employees are using or that can be purchased to improve the way =
employees work. In addition, they have high emotional intelligence =
because the role is focused on making sure employees are fulfilled and =
content. The executives have to be able to talk and engage with =
employees on their pain points regarding working from home or in the =
office and how they can work more efficiently. The combination of tech =
and human resources, said King, is oriented toward addressing what keeps =
employees from getting their work done and leverages people analytics.

=E2=80=9CThey can=E2=80=99t just be a back-end technology nerd with no =
EQ and no people skills,=E2=80=9D said King. =E2=80=9CThis is a =
touchier, feelier role when you come down to it, and it=E2=80=99s all =
focused on making people happy.=E2=80=9D=20

Companies have long focused on customer and client experience, but the =
pandemic and the shift to digital and hybrid corporate headquarters and =
offices is driving them to pay more attention to the employee experience =
role. King also pointed to =E2=80=9CThe Great Resignation=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94 a term coined to describe the phenomenon in which thousands of =
employees have left their jobs without anything else lined up because =
they are unhappy with their workplace and want more flexibility, for =
example =E2=80=94 as another underlying driver.=20

King pointed out that some companies have lagged in engaging directly =
with employees and understanding what their return to work looks like or =
will look like. For instance, a recent Washington Post article =
<https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2021/09/27/return-to-work-in-p=
erson-hybrid/?utm_campaign=3Dwp_main&utm_medium=3Dsocial&utm_source=3Dtwi=
tter>  described how some employees have returned to offices only to be =
faced with safety protocols that require them to interact with =
colleagues using Microsoft Teams, Google Meet, Zoom and Slack =E2=80=94 =
the same as they would if they were still working from home.=20

King said that type of disconnect could point to a C-suite that wants =
employees in the office but hasn=E2=80=99t thought through what the =
return is like for employees on a day-to-day basis.=20

=E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re going into the office and doing the exact =
same thing you=E2=80=99d be doing at home, there=E2=80=99s no =
point,=E2=80=9D said King. =E2=80=9CThat might suggest that the C-suite =
is calling the shots =E2=80=94 they want you to be in the office, so =
you=E2=80=99re going in.=E2=80=9D

That approach could cause companies to fall behind in recruiting and in =
retention.=20

=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s such a candidate hiring market right now,=E2=80=9D =
said King. =E2=80=9CCompanies are saying, =E2=80=98We need to do =
whatever we can to attract talent, and if that means allowing them to =
work totally remotely, that=E2=80=99s fine.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

While some companies have =E2=80=9Cstodgy leadership=E2=80=9D that =
hasn=E2=80=99t yet evolved, others are overly catering to employees, he =
said. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a sense of the inmates are running the =
asylum,=E2=80=9D said King.

Broadly, there has been a significant shift in the way some C-suites and =
boards think about employees since the pandemic, said Liz Fosslien, head =
of content at workplace culture and inclusion firm Humu and co-author of =
the book =E2=80=9CNo Hard Feelings: The Secret Power of Embracing =
Emotions at Work.=E2=80=9D Well-being has become top of mind along with =
figuring out how a company should support the quantitative, technical =
needs of employees who are working in company offices, at home or both =
while also creating deeper connections while working remotely.=20

=E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re working from home, it matters a little less =
if you work at Facebook versus Google,=E2=80=9D said Fosslien. =
=E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re in your living room, there=E2=80=99s a =
different logo, but it=E2=80=99s a similar job.=E2=80=9D

Some employees really want to be in the office full-time while others =
want to work from home permanently. Others want flexibility. In =
addition, the emotional needs of employees have shifted dramatically in =
the past 18 months and have created lasting requirements related to =
mental health that employees are looking to companies to provide, said =
Fosslien.=20

In order to retain employees and to be attractive in terms of =
recruiting, companies are increasingly focusing more intentionally on =
employee experience and equipping managers with the tools they need to =
effectively talk about emotions at work, she said.=20

More buttoned-up, traditional organizations such as law firms and =
financial services companies are seeking out workshops and learning =
opportunities for managers to provide them with skills to handle the =
emotional needs of employees, she said. =E2=80=9CPeople are feeling a =
lot of things, and they don=E2=80=99t really know how to touch =
that.=E2=80=9D

Prior to the pandemic, employee experience roles were traditionally =
under the domain of the chief people or chief human resources officer. =
As employee experience has become more data driven, chief information =
officers are increasingly being looped into employee experience =
conversations because there are privacy concerns and because that data =
piece is essential to understanding the needs of employees, explained =
Fosslien.=20

The role also underscores the broader, governance-focused shift to =
corporate purpose and the needs of stakeholders and communities.=20

Previously, learning and development at some companies wasn=E2=80=99t as =
serious or embedded into organization as it is now, Fosslien noted. She =
recalled an executive once telling her that such programs were like =
perfume. =E2=80=9CYou spray some stuff in the air and it smells good, =
and then a day later it=E2=80=99s gone,=E2=80=9D she recalled.=20

